{"title_page": "Clara Ragaz", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name          = Clara Ragaz\n| image         = RagazClara Leonhard 1923.jpg\n| alt           = <!-- descriptive text for use by speech synthesis (text-to-speech) software -->\n| caption       = Clara and Leonhard Ragaz, 1923\n| birth_name    = Clara Nadig\n| birth_date    = {{Birth date|1874|03|30|df=y}}\n| birth_place   = [[Chur]], [[Switzerland]]\n| death_date    = {{Death date and age|1957|10|07|1874|03|30|df=y}}\n| death_place   = [[Z\u00fcrich]], Switzerland\n| nationality   = Swiss\n| other_names   = Clara Ragaz-Nadig\n| occupation    = teacher, pacifist\n| years_active  = 1892\u20131946\n| known_for     =\n| notable_works =\n}}\n\n'''Clara Ragaz''' (30 March 1874 \u2013 7 October 1957) was one of the most noted Swiss feminist [[pacifist]]s of the first half of the twentieth century. She was a founder of the Swiss Federation of Abstinent Women, an organization that supported the [[temperance movement]] in Switzerland. She served as the co-International chair of the [[Women's International League for Peace and Freedom]] (WILPF) from 1929 to 1946.\n\n==Early life==\nClara Nadig was born on 30 March 1874 in [[Chur]], in the [[Grisons]] [[Cantons of Switzerland|canton]] of [[Switzerland]] to Christina (n\u00e9e Plattner) and Johann Josua Nadig. She studied to be a teacher, completing her training in 1892 at the [[normal school]] in [[Aarau]].{{sfn|Studer|2012}}\n\n==Career==\nNadig first taught in England and France before returning to Switzerland. She taught in a Sunday school and became involved in missionary work, which is how she met the social activist [[Leonhard Ragaz]] in 1893,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://womenvotepeace.com/women/clara-ragaz-bio/|title=Clara Ragaz- bio|last=HeidiM|website=Women Vote Peace|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-06}}</ref> whom she married in 1901.{{sfn|Schelbert|2014|p=299}} She took a teaching position in the [[Engadin]] valley,{{sfn|Studer|2012}} while her husband served as the chief Protestant cleric of Chur between 1902 and 1906.{{sfn|Schelbert|2014|p=299}} In 1902, she was one of the founders of the Swiss Federation of Abstinent Women ({{lang-de|Schweiz Bundes abstinenter Frauen}}),{{sfn|Studer|2012}} an arm of the international [[temperance movement]] in Switzerland.{{sfn|Trechsel|2015}} In 1907, she joined the feminist organization [[Union for the Advancement of Women]] ({{lang-de|Union f\u00fcr Frauenbestrebungen}}),{{sfn|Studer|2012}} when the couple were in [[Bern]] and her husband served as a pastor for the [[Basel Minster]]. In 1908, they moved to [[Z\u00fcrich]], where Ragaz continued teaching and her husband was engaged as a professor of theology at the [[University of Zurich]].{{sfn|Schelbert|2014|p=299}} In Z\u00fcrich Ragaz joined the buyer's collective known as the Social Buyer's League ({{lang-de|Sozialen K\u00e4uferliga}}), which aimed at improving the situation of workers through conscious buying methods of consumers, and remained a part of the group until 1915.{{sfn|Studer|2012}} Together with [[Emma Pieczynska-Reichenbach]] she worked towards improving the minimum wage of female workers, shorter working hours, and better working conditions.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://womenvotepeace.com/women/clara-ragaz-bio/|title=Clara Ragaz- bio|last=HeidiM|website=Women Vote Peace|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-06}}</ref>\n\nIn 1909, Ragaz served as the director of the Swiss Home Works Exhibition ({{lang-de|Schweiz Heimarbeitsausstellung}}),{{sfn|Studer|2012}} which featured spinning, straw works, cobbling and other handcrafted items created by women, but also discussed the problems of working women, unsanitary conditions and child labor practices.{{sfn|''Die Vork\u00e4mpferin''|1909|p=1-2}} In 1913, she joined the [[Socialist Party of Switzerland]] and along with her husband practiced [[religious socialism]], believing that Christian faith required a social conscience that focused on helping working class people.{{sfn|Schelbert|2014|p=300}} In 1915, Ragaz co-founded the Committee for a Lasting Peace (German: ''Komitee f\u00fcr einen dauernden Frieden'')<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://womenvotepeace.com/women/clara-ragaz-bio/|title=Clara Ragaz- bio|last=HeidiM|website=Women Vote Peace|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-06}}</ref> and would serve as its president until 1946.{{sfn|Studer|2012}} That same year, she published ''Women in Peace'' from a talk she had given. In 1919 she played a key role in bringing the Congress of Zurich to the city, which led to the foundation of the [[Women's International League for Peace and Freedom]].<ref>{{Cite book|last=Siegel|first=Mona|title=Peace on our terms: the global battle for women's rights after the First World War|publisher=Columbia University Press|year=2020|isbn=9780231551182|location=|pages=130-135}}</ref> The meeting followed on from the 1915 Hague Congress of Women, held by feminist internationalist women seeking to end World War 1. Ragaz was the opening speaker for the Congress of Zurich, alongside renowned feminist [[Jane Addams]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://womenvotepeace.com/zurich-congress-1919/|title=Zurich Congress 1919|website=Women Vote Peace|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-06}}</ref> She continued to work with the international WILPF in Geneva{{sfn|Schelbert|2014|p=300}}. In 1921, she published a translation of ''Tagore as Educator'' by [[Emma Pieczynska-Reichenbach]]. That same year, her husband quit his university job and the couple moved to the [[Aussersihl]] district to live among the workers there. They were committed to the social welfare of the working class and Ragaz began giving lectures at the Social School for Women ({{lang-de|Sozialen Frauenschule}}).{{sfn|Studer|2012}}\n\nRagaz translated the work ''Religious Foundations of the Social Gospel'' by [[Walter Rauschenbusch]], one of his most influential books, into German in 1922.{{sfn|Schelbert|2014|p=300}}{{sfn|Macchia|Chung|2002|p=}} In 1929, Ragaz succeeded [[Jane Addams]] as one of the co-International Chairs of the WILPF. Because of the volume of work to be done, it was decided that the responsibilities Addams had carried were to be shared with [[Gertrud Baer]] and [[Emily Greene Balch]].{{sfn|Swarthmore College Peace Collection|1992}}{{sfn|Longman|1937|p=5}}{{sfn|Foster|1995|p=241}} That same year, she was appointed as the vice president of the boarding school at the Social School for Women and served in that capacity until 1946.{{sfn|Studer|2012}} Ragaz, Baer, and Balch, who was later replaced by [[Kathleen Innes]] steered the WILPF during the difficult war years, when defending borders and simultaneously advocating an anti-war stance often were at odds.{{sfn|Foster|1995|pp=241, 267}} Both she and her husband resigned from the socialist party in 1935 over the stance of national defense.{{sfn|Studer|2012}} She remained active in the pacifist movement until the war ended.{{sfn|Swarthmore College Peace Collection|1992}}\n\n==Death and legacy==\nRagaz died on 7 October 1957 in Zurich.{{sfn|Studer|2012}} In 2015, a lecture series honoring her pacifist work was presented by the Association of Eastern Swiss Women in [[St. Gallen]], Switzerland.{{sfn|Be\u00e9ry|2015}}\n\n== References ==\n===Citations===\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n===Bibliography===\n{{refbegin|30em}}\n* {{cite web|ref=harv|last1=Be\u00e9ry|first1=Martha|title=Clara Ragaz, 1874\u20131957|url=https://www.ostschweizerinnen.ch/veranstaltungen/clara-ragaz-1874-1957/|website=Ostschweizerinnen|publisher=The Association of Eastern Swiss Women|accessdate=21 August 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170821211833/https://www.ostschweizerinnen.ch/veranstaltungen/clara-ragaz-1874-1957/|archivedate=21 August 2017|location=St. Gallen, Switzerland|language=German|date=11 November 2015}}\n* {{cite book|ref=harv|last=Foster|first=Carrie A.|title=The Women and the Warriors: The U.S. Section of the Women's International League for Peace and Freedom, 1915\u20131946|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=SiSk_AkVofAC&pg=PA179|year=1995|publisher=Syracuse University Press|location=Syracuse, New York|isbn=978-0-8156-2662-6}}\n* {{cite news|ref=harv|last1=Longman|first1=Dorothy|title=Womankind|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/susun-wilkinson-celebrity-clipping-aug-06-1937-347429/|accessdate=31 July 2017|publisher=[[The Jewish Exponent]]|date=6 August 1937|location=Philadelphia, Pennsylvania|page=5|via = [[Newspaperarchive.com]]}} {{open access}}\n* {{cite book|ref=harv|last1=Macchia|first1=Frank D.|last2=Chung|first2=Paul S.|title=Theology Between the East and West: A Radical Legacy: Essays in Honor of Jan Milic Lochman|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Q9lKAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA233|year=2002|publisher=Wipf and Stock Publishers|location=Eugene, Oregon|isbn=978-1-59244-087-0}}\n* {{cite book|ref=harv|last=Schelbert|first=Leo|title=Historical Dictionary of Switzerland|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=XRevAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA299|edition=2nd|year=2014|publisher=Rowman & Littlefield Publishers|location=Lanham, Maryland|isbn=978-1-4422-3352-2|chapter=Ragaz, Clara Nadig (1874-1957)|pages=299\u2013300}}\n* {{cite web|ref=harv|last1=Studer|first1=Brigitte|title=Ragaz(-Nadig), Clara|url=http://www.hls-dhs-dss.ch/textes/d/D10792.php|website=Historischen Lexikon der Schweiz|accessdate=21 August 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170624063713/http://www.hls-dhs-dss.ch/textes/d/D10792.php|archivedate=24 June 2017|location=Bern, Switzerland|language=German|date=12 January 2012}}\n* {{cite web|ref=harv|last1=Trechsel|first1=Rolf|title=Abstinenzbewegung|url=http://www.hls-dhs-dss.ch/textes/d/D16445.php|website=Historischen Lexikon der Schweiz|accessdate=21 August 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160919062535/http://www.hls-dhs-dss.ch/textes/d/D16445.php|archivedate=19 September 2016|location=Bern, Switzerland|language=German|date=21 January 2015}}\n* {{cite book|ref=harv|last1=Wiltsher|first1=Anne|title=Most Dangerous Women: Feminist Peace Campaigners of the Great War|date=1985|publisher=Pandora Press|location=London, England|isbn=0-86358-010-6|edition=1st|url=https://archive.org/stream/mostdangerouswom00anne_0#page/206/mode/1up/search/ragaz}}\n* {{cite journal|ref={{harvid|''Die Vork\u00e4mpferin''|1909}}|author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.-->|title=Von der Heimarbeit-Ausstellung in Z\u00fcrich|journal=Die Vork\u00e4mpferin|date=1 August 1909|volume=IV|issue=9|pages=1\u20132|doi=10.5169/seals-349972|url=http://www.e-periodica.ch/digbib/view?pid=vor-001:1909:4::202|accessdate=21 August 2017|trans-title=From the Home Works Exhibition in Zurich|publisher=Schweiz Arbeiterinnenverbanes|location=Z\u00fcrich, Switzerland|language=German}}\n* {{cite web|ref={{harvid|Swarthmore College Peace Collection|1992}}|author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.-->|title=Women\u2019s International League for Peace and Freedom Collection (DG043)|url=https://www.swarthmore.edu/library/peace/DG026-050/dg043wilpf/Part%20II-Int%27l-AppenA.htm|website=[[Swarthmore College]]|publisher=Swarthmore College Peace Collection|accessdate=1 August 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304192535/https://www.swarthmore.edu/library/peace/DG026-050/dg043wilpf/Part%20II-Int'l-AppenA.htm|archivedate=4 March 2016|location=Swarthmore, Pennsylvania|date=1992}}\n{{refend}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ragaz, Clara}}\n[[Category:1874 births]]\n[[Category:1957 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Chur]]\n[[Category:Swiss women's rights activists]]\n[[Category:Pacifist feminists]]\n[[Category:Swiss pacifists]]\n[[Category:Women's International League for Peace and Freedom people]]\n[[Category:Socialist feminists]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name          = Clara Ragaz\n| image         = RagazClara Leonhard 1923.jpg\n| alt           = <!-- descriptive text for use by speech synthesis (text-to-speech) software -->\n| caption       = Clara and Leonhard Ragaz, 1923\n| birth_name    = Clara Nadig\n| birth_date    = {{Birth date|1874|03|30|df=y}}\n| birth_place   = [[Chur]], [[Switzerland]]\n| death_date    = {{Death date and age|1957|10|07|1874|03|30|df=y}}\n| death_place   = [[Z\u00fcrich]], Switzerland\n| nationality   = Swiss\n| other_names   = Clara Ragaz-Nadig\n| occupation    = teacher, pacifist\n| years_active  = 1892\u20131946\n| known_for     =\n| notable_works =\n}}\n\n'''Clara Ragaz''' (30 March 1874 \u2013 7 October 1957) was one of the most noted Swiss feminist [[pacifist]]s of the first half of the twentieth century. She was a founder of the Swiss Federation of Abstinent Women, an organization which supported the [[temperance movement]] in Switzerland. She served as the co-International chair of the [[Women's International League for Peace and Freedom]] (WILPF) from 1929 to 1946.\n\n==Early life==\nClara Nadig was born on 30 March 1874 in [[Chur]], in the [[Grisons]] [[Cantons of Switzerland|canton]] of [[Switzerland]] to Christina (n\u00e9e Plattner) and Johann Josua Nadig. She studied to be a teacher, completing her training in 1892 at the [[normal school]] in [[Aarau]].{{sfn|Studer|2012}}\n\n==Career==\nNadig first taught in England and France before returning to Switzerland. She taught in a Sunday school and became involved in missionary work, which is how she met the social activist [[Leonhard Ragaz]] in 1893,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://womenvotepeace.com/women/clara-ragaz-bio/|title=Clara Ragaz- bio|last=HeidiM|website=Women Vote Peace|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-06}}</ref> whom she married in 1901.{{sfn|Schelbert|2014|p=299}} She took a teaching position in the [[Engadin]] valley,{{sfn|Studer|2012}} while her husband served as the chief Protestant cleric of Chur between 1902 and 1906.{{sfn|Schelbert|2014|p=299}} In 1902, she was one of the founders of the Swiss Federation of Abstinent Women ({{lang-de|Schweiz Bundes abstinenter Frauen}}),{{sfn|Studer|2012}} an arm of the international [[temperance movement]] in Switzerland.{{sfn|Trechsel|2015}} In 1907, she joined the feminist organization [[Union for the Advancement of Women]] ({{lang-de|Union f\u00fcr Frauenbestrebungen}}),{{sfn|Studer|2012}} when the couple were in [[Bern]] and her husband served as a pastor for the [[Basel Minster]]. In 1908, they moved to [[Z\u00fcrich]], where Ragaz continued teaching and her husband was engaged as a professor of theology at the [[University of Zurich]].{{sfn|Schelbert|2014|p=299}} In Z\u00fcrich Ragaz joined the buyer's collective known as the Social Buyer's League ({{lang-de|Sozialen K\u00e4uferliga}}), which aimed at improving the situation of workers through conscious buying methods of consumers, and remained a part of the group until 1915.{{sfn|Studer|2012}} Together with [[Emma Pieczynska-Reichenbach]] she worked towards improving the minimum wage of female workers, shorter working hours, and better working conditions.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://womenvotepeace.com/women/clara-ragaz-bio/|title=Clara Ragaz- bio|last=HeidiM|website=Women Vote Peace|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-06}}</ref>\n\nIn 1909, Ragaz served as the director of the Swiss Home Works Exhibition ({{lang-de|Schweiz Heimarbeitsausstellung}}),{{sfn|Studer|2012}} which featured spinning, straw works, cobbling and other handcrafted items created by women, but also discussed the problems of working women, unsanitary conditions and child labor practices.{{sfn|''Die Vork\u00e4mpferin''|1909|p=1-2}} In 1913, she joined the [[Socialist Party of Switzerland]] and along with her husband practiced [[religious socialism]], believing that Christian faith required a social conscience that focused on helping working class people.{{sfn|Schelbert|2014|p=300}} In 1915, Ragaz co-founded the Committee for a Lasting Peace (German: ''Komitee f\u00fcr einen dauernden Frieden'')<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://womenvotepeace.com/women/clara-ragaz-bio/|title=Clara Ragaz- bio|last=HeidiM|website=Women Vote Peace|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-06}}</ref> and would serve as its president until 1946.{{sfn|Studer|2012}} That same year, she published ''Women in Peace'' from a talk she had given. In 1919 she played a key role in bringing the Congress of Zurich to the city, which led to the foundation of the [[Women's International League for Peace and Freedom]].<ref>{{Cite book|last=Siegel|first=Mona|title=Peace on our terms: the global battle for women's rights after the First World War|publisher=Columbia University Press|year=2020|isbn=9780231551182|location=|pages=130-135}}</ref> The meeting followed on from the 1915 Hague Congress of Women, held by feminist internationalist women seeking to end World War 1. Ragaz was the opening speaker for the Congress of Zurich, alongside renowned feminist [[Jane Addams]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://womenvotepeace.com/zurich-congress-1919/|title=Zurich Congress 1919|website=Women Vote Peace|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-06}}</ref> She continued to work with the international WILPF in Geneva{{sfn|Schelbert|2014|p=300}}. In 1921, she published a translation of ''Tagore as Educator'' by [[Emma Pieczynska-Reichenbach]]. That same year, her husband quit his university job and the couple moved to the [[Aussersihl]] district to live among the workers there. They were committed to the social welfare of the working class and Ragaz began giving lectures at the Social School for Women ({{lang-de|Sozialen Frauenschule}}).{{sfn|Studer|2012}}\n\nRagaz translated the work ''Religious Foundations of the Social Gospel'' by [[Walter Rauschenbusch]], one of his most influential books, into German in 1922.{{sfn|Schelbert|2014|p=300}}{{sfn|Macchia|Chung|2002|p=}} In 1929, Ragaz succeeded [[Jane Addams]] as one of the co-International Chairs of the WILPF. Because of the volume of work to be done, it was decided that the responsibilities Addams had carried were to be shared with [[Gertrud Baer]] and [[Emily Greene Balch]].{{sfn|Swarthmore College Peace Collection|1992}}{{sfn|Longman|1937|p=5}}{{sfn|Foster|1995|p=241}} That same year, she was appointed as the vice president of the boarding school at the Social School for Women and served in that capacity until 1946.{{sfn|Studer|2012}} Ragaz, Baer, and Balch, who was later replaced by [[Kathleen Innes]] steered the WILPF during the difficult war years, when defending borders and simultaneously advocating an anti-war stance often were at odds.{{sfn|Foster|1995|pp=241, 267}} Both she and her husband resigned from the socialist party in 1935 over the stance of national defense.{{sfn|Studer|2012}} She remained active in the pacifist movement until the war ended.{{sfn|Swarthmore College Peace Collection|1992}}\n\n==Death and legacy==\nRagaz died on 7 October 1957 in Zurich.{{sfn|Studer|2012}} In 2015, a lecture series honoring her pacifist work was presented by the Association of Eastern Swiss Women in [[St. Gallen]], Switzerland.{{sfn|Be\u00e9ry|2015}}\n\n== References ==\n===Citations===\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n===Bibliography===\n{{refbegin|30em}}\n* {{cite web|ref=harv|last1=Be\u00e9ry|first1=Martha|title=Clara Ragaz, 1874\u20131957|url=https://www.ostschweizerinnen.ch/veranstaltungen/clara-ragaz-1874-1957/|website=Ostschweizerinnen|publisher=The Association of Eastern Swiss Women|accessdate=21 August 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170821211833/https://www.ostschweizerinnen.ch/veranstaltungen/clara-ragaz-1874-1957/|archivedate=21 August 2017|location=St. Gallen, Switzerland|language=German|date=11 November 2015}}\n* {{cite book|ref=harv|last=Foster|first=Carrie A.|title=The Women and the Warriors: The U.S. Section of the Women's International League for Peace and Freedom, 1915\u20131946|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=SiSk_AkVofAC&pg=PA179|year=1995|publisher=Syracuse University Press|location=Syracuse, New York|isbn=978-0-8156-2662-6}}\n* {{cite news|ref=harv|last1=Longman|first1=Dorothy|title=Womankind|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/susun-wilkinson-celebrity-clipping-aug-06-1937-347429/|accessdate=31 July 2017|publisher=[[The Jewish Exponent]]|date=6 August 1937|location=Philadelphia, Pennsylvania|page=5|via = [[Newspaperarchive.com]]}} {{open access}}\n* {{cite book|ref=harv|last1=Macchia|first1=Frank D.|last2=Chung|first2=Paul S.|title=Theology Between the East and West: A Radical Legacy: Essays in Honor of Jan Milic Lochman|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Q9lKAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA233|year=2002|publisher=Wipf and Stock Publishers|location=Eugene, Oregon|isbn=978-1-59244-087-0}}\n* {{cite book|ref=harv|last=Schelbert|first=Leo|title=Historical Dictionary of Switzerland|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=XRevAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA299|edition=2nd|year=2014|publisher=Rowman & Littlefield Publishers|location=Lanham, Maryland|isbn=978-1-4422-3352-2|chapter=Ragaz, Clara Nadig (1874-1957)|pages=299\u2013300}}\n* {{cite web|ref=harv|last1=Studer|first1=Brigitte|title=Ragaz(-Nadig), Clara|url=http://www.hls-dhs-dss.ch/textes/d/D10792.php|website=Historischen Lexikon der Schweiz|accessdate=21 August 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170624063713/http://www.hls-dhs-dss.ch/textes/d/D10792.php|archivedate=24 June 2017|location=Bern, Switzerand|language=German|date=12 January 2012}}\n* {{cite web|ref=harv|last1=Trechsel|first1=Rolf|title=Abstinenzbewegung|url=http://www.hls-dhs-dss.ch/textes/d/D16445.php|website=Historischen Lexikon der Schweiz|accessdate=21 August 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160919062535/http://www.hls-dhs-dss.ch/textes/d/D16445.php|archivedate=19 September 2016|location=Bern, Switzerand|language=German|date=21 January 2015}}\n* {{cite book|ref=harv|last1=Wiltsher|first1=Anne|title=Most Dangerous Women: Feminist Peace Campaigners of the Great War|date=1985|publisher=Pandora Press|location=London, England|isbn=0-86358-010-6|edition=1st|url=https://archive.org/stream/mostdangerouswom00anne_0#page/206/mode/1up/search/ragaz}}\n* {{cite journal|ref={{harvid|''Die Vork\u00e4mpferin''|1909}}|author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.-->|title=Von der Heimarbeit-Ausstellung in Z\u00fcrich|journal=Die Vork\u00e4mpferin|date=1 August 1909|volume=IV|issue=9|pages=1\u20132|doi=10.5169/seals-349972|url=http://www.e-periodica.ch/digbib/view?pid=vor-001:1909:4::202|accessdate=21 August 2017|trans-title=From the Home Works Exhibition in Zurich|publisher=Schweiz Arbeiterinnenverbanes|location=Z\u00fcrich, Switzerland|language=German}}\n* {{cite web|ref={{harvid|Swarthmore College Peace Collection|1992}}|author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.-->|title=Women\u2019s International League for Peace and Freedom Collection (DG043)|url=https://www.swarthmore.edu/library/peace/DG026-050/dg043wilpf/Part%20II-Int%27l-AppenA.htm|website=[[Swarthmore College]]|publisher=Swarthmore College Peace Collection|accessdate=1 August 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304192535/https://www.swarthmore.edu/library/peace/DG026-050/dg043wilpf/Part%20II-Int'l-AppenA.htm|archivedate=4 March 2016|location=Swarthmore, Pennsylvania|date=1992}}\n{{refend}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ragaz, Clara}}\n[[Category:1874 births]]\n[[Category:1957 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Chur]]\n[[Category:Swiss women's rights activists]]\n[[Category:Pacifist feminists]]\n[[Category:Swiss pacifists]]\n[[Category:Women's International League for Peace and Freedom people]]\n[[Category:Socialist feminists]]\n", "name_user": "LilHelpa", "label": "safe", "comment": "typos; mnr copy edit", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Clara_Ragaz"}
